caption: La Vara is a must. Fantastic food, fun drinks, and beautiful chic atmosphere. I can’t believe they’re closed for the season, but I hope to see them open once indoor dining opens. It is surely the best restaurant in Brooklyn Heights/Cobble Hill area.

Too expensive and pretentsious, combination of tastes and size of portions doesn't justify price. In addition when opening in limited conditions and half of the menu is not serving, better not to open at all.
What a great restaurant. So many amazing dishes with fresh ingredients. The servers were super friendly and did not steer me wrong with their recommendations. This was well worth the drive!
This restaurant has very good food. Only tried take out because of COVID but good lord was the food top notch.

Start to finish, this was a phenomenal meal. There wasn’t a single thing that I wouldn’t have eaten.  For me the standouts include the kanpachi crudo and their “paella”. I’m already looking forward to my next time at La Vara
Really yummy food and good service! The lobster rise was particularly good!
Absolutely the best prepared best tasting Chicken anywhere. The seasoning is phenomenal. Meticulously cooked by his special procedures and spices!
Great service, great vibe, inventive fare. Roasted veggies and suckling pig are a must.
Great staff and food that will keep you there for hours!
the gazpacho!!

Love.
We tried 8 dishes. Every single one was scrumptious!! Service was top notch. It's now a must go whenever I'm in NY.

This is supposed to be such a sweet neighborhood gem but it can really be hit or miss. Dinner has been great in the past but we came for brunch and the croquetas were delivered cold on the inside. Then the lamb burger was so dry it was inedible, and sort of sad on a grilled bun with a few sprigs of arugula. The tortillita de Gambas was redeeming and delicious.

Spectacular!  The place is on the smaller side, but it only works to provide a more cozy, intimate feeling.  The food was incredible. The menu is composed of tapas and small plates. Our waitress recommended 2-3 dishes per person, so my girlfriend and I got 5. It was a good amount of food and dear God was it delicious.  The staff kept our plates coming out one at a time in good rhythm as we finished each course.  Our server was knowledgeable, provided great opinions, and absolutely lovely.  Price is high, but I would say well worth it for a special occasion. (Came out to $240ish without tip for 2 ppl, wine, and dessert).
Great service, will return.
Nice place, nice staff. DELICIOUS FOOD.
Food was good but felt that the experience would have been drastically improved if the portion sizes were even a tiny bit larger for the price point.
Simply amazing
My favorite tapas place! I recommend the Migas Aragonesas and the olive oil ice cream--but I've never been disappointed by a dish.
Great food and ambience. The value for money is quite decent given that it's clearly a high value experience. They could make the garden a bit nicer with some decorations or so perhaps.

Dined here 3 times, and each time the food is amazing. Everything is fresh and really delicious, perfectly seasoned. I like that they keep some dishes and rotate others. Each time I have been there I have tried one of the daily specials. Never disappointed.

My family ate here last night and we were totally impressed with the food. We ordered 15 dishes from the menu. They are Tapas of varying sizes and there were 5 of us. Two got mixed reviews, the cod and the lamb breast but the rest of the dishes we ordered were considered delicious by all. The "but" in the title is about the noise level and space. It was a din;so loud that we could hardly hear each speak. The space is small and everyone is packed in like sardines. Our table was a crescent banquette right next to the bar. People waiting to be seated were draped by our table. I realize this is out of their control but it is definitely intrusive and impacted on our enjoyment. Amy W. our server was a delight! So this is great cooking but you pay a price in addition to the bill.

Incredible!

Truly an exceptional dining experience. Service was flawless, and the food. Good lord, the food. Crispy eggplant. 🔥 Torn bread with chorizo. 🔥 You get the point. Come here, often.

Had such a delicious meal at La Vara. We visited on a holiday weekend and went right when they opened for dinner and there was already a line. That’s a good thing in NYC because you know it will be good. Our waitress was great and helped us pick the right amount of dishes to share. Everything was very balanced and fresh from the cocktails to savories to dessert. Very deserving of a Michelin Star.

Overpriced and overhyped! Pretty disappointed with the food in general; the artichokes were hard, couldn’t swallow the whole thing. The main courses are disproportionate. The rabbit was like an appetizer, so small; $21 for two small medallions of meat approx two inches each, and doesn’t come with any side.  My friend had the pork; a huge chunk of meat which she described as below the average she generally has. Finally, for dessert; the Torta de Santiago is too dry while the frozen yoghurt, beware, if you think you’re better off having frozen yoghurt than ice cream think twice, the yoghurt comes with a ‘side’ of meringues pieces so sugary makes you cringe.
Delicious food and coffee. We enjoyed it but the food was not warm. It was OK. Knowing it has a michelin, I was expecting something perfect.
Amazing

This is an excellent restaurant. Unfortunately only 3* though due to one of the servers. On the plus side the food is excellent. Some very memorable dishes, especially the octopus and also the torn bread, chorizo, grape and egg. Plus it’s excellent value for money for the quality of the food.  Unfortunately the server who opened our wine wasn’t so good. She was struggling to open the bottle of wine (partly because she didn’t really seem to know how to use the corkscrew properly). She then snapped the cork in half and said “I’ll go and get you a fresh bottle”. She reappeared 30s later with an open bottle which was suspicious (rather than opening a new one in front of us). I was going to ask for her to bring the cork but wasn’t really necessary as when she poured the wine to taste it clearly had cork floating in it. I sent it back and asked to be bought a fresh bottle opened at the table. I really don’t think this is OK and was a real shame given what was an otherwise excellent meal. I’d hope it’s just a misjudgement on the part of one server, but even so suggests some training and oversight is needed as isn’t really acceptable.

No question the best quality food in Brooklyn..cucumber & grain salad...crispy eggplant with fondue...fish of the day...intimate space with excellent bartending. If you cant snag a table at least grab a seat at the bar for full service. Two thumbs way up!
The food was sooo delicious! We have really enjoyed ourselves. I would totally recommend this place to everyone who visits NYC!

Wonderful dining experience. Great staff and delicious dishes.. Artichoke anchovy aioli starter, chicken-hearts-salad, lamb-main dish was every bit as tasty as appetizing to the eye..

WOW! Very delicious. Didn't think I could ever enjoy sardines but I did there!!! For a Michelin rated place prices are reasonable . Service is superbe. Attentive without being too much. Will definitely go again.

Great Spanish restaurant in a quaint spot. Tasted not only the Spanish but also catallan and Moorish influences. Some real surprises on the menu. Would definitely go again.

Excellent food in an informal, pleasant ambiance, good service and bad pacing. We were four, and ordered 13 dishes from the menu, roughly according to the recommendation of our lovely waiter. Dishes are ordered all together and our waiter promised us a layered serving that will optimally organize our meal. These were just words, since in the next 20-25 munutes, 9 out of the 13 dishes arrived, and that was a hint that no one in the kitchen cared about layers, or order or the fact that people come to enjoy a relaxed evening with excellent food, and not be force-fed and made to leave as fast as humanly possible. At the 9th dish I remarked on this to the waiter, who eventually put a break on the rollercoaster wheels. The food itself is for the most part fantastic. We had 4 of the specials and the rest from the menu, and besides the octopus dish, which in my taste was too sweet and covered the delicate flavor of the excellently prepared octopus, everything was spot on. And so were the desserts, which included a superlative olive oil helado. Prices are decent, and we will gladly come back, hoping that the kitchen will be more respectful of the dining experience.
Small, great ambience, friendly staff. Delicious, complex Mexican food. Excellent coffee. Well priced. Michelin star.
Ma please better churros in Corona ,Queens  and get some real dulce de leche the dollar is stong in Argentina ....

La Vara has the low-key vibe and warmth of a neighborhood joint but the imagination and flavor of a serious—and seriously good—restaurant. I don't think I've ever had a bad dish. Perennial standouts include the croquetas (filling changes daily), the berenjenas (breaded eggplant slivers nestled in a sauce of cheese and honey), the lamb meatballs, and the rabbit; but be sure to check the specials, of which there are typically several, and lean hard into anything from the sea 'cause it'll almost surely be outstanding. There are some good and fascinating wine options whether by bottle or glass, and the service is friendly but chill. Can't recommend this place highly enough.
Exceptional
Great Spanish tapas place deserving of the Michelin star it has earned. Bright flavors and sophisticated pairings.  Tremendous.
Too much hype about nothing.  Waited almost a month to get in this restaurant.   The expectations were very high.  Although the food was good, it was not a month-wait-good.

Been buying spices here for years. They have a huge collection of teas, spices, pickles a d speciality foods from around the world. Well with the trip if you are into Indian or Asian cooking. I have a personal weakness for spicy lime pickle.
Food and service was great but I felt options were limited for brunch. Sangria was amazing! Overall great experience and the neighborhood is really nice.
Overpriced,mediocre food.they lost the meeting of tapas at this place!

This is truly a local gem: friendly (and cute) staff and service, delicious food, edgy and yet mature atmosphere.  What else does one need?  The dishes include a variety of brunch classics with an organic and healthy spin (okay, maybe not the churros, but they’re delicious anyway).  Make a reservation if you plan on visiting during the weekend brunch hours.  Otherwise, plan a a stroll around beautiful Cobble Hill as you wait.
Every meal I have here is fantastic.
Wow! Such a great experience. Food was exceptional, service was flawless. Really liked how the kitchen decides the courses for you. Dessert fell a little short of the rest of the meal.
Amazing food. Intimate setting. Would definitely go again.
Not bad , but over priced for tiny tapas
Absolutely delicious. Our group got a little of everything to share and nothing disappointed. Lots of specials too. Great sangria & desserts to top it off. Highly recommend

(Translated by Google) An intimate and cozy restaurant. Good service but there were some situations where I looked for the waitress for a while. Delicious and creative food, however a few disappointments: the portion of the torn bread with tsuriso and yolk was unbalanced, too oily and spicy, as for the handmade pasta, in a sauce of spicy, heavy oil, with the same taste (and lack of salt and too much paprika) of The tsuriso dish, lacking a balance and refreshing element. I found no reason to finish them. Other than that everything else was great.  (Original) מסעדה אינטימית וחמימה. שירות טוב אך היו כמה מצבים שבהם חיפשתי את המלצרית זמן מה. אוכל טעים ויצירתי, עם זאת כמה אכזבות: המנה של הלחם הקרוע עם צוריסו וחלמון הייתה לא מאוזנת, שמנה ומתובלת מידי, כנ"ל לגבי הפסטה בעבודת יד, ברוטב של שמן מתובל, כבדה, עם אותו טעם (וחוסר במלח ויותר מדי פפריקה) של מנת הצוריסו, חסרת אלמנט מאזן ומרענן. לא מצאתי סיבה לסיים אותן. מלבד זאת כל השאר היה נהדר.
Absolutely delicious. Expensive but worth every single dollar. We had half of the menu and where not disappointed by any item. Fantastic wine selection. Knowledgeable staff.
Lovely location! The food was ABSOLUTELY delicious! Best food in new york city! Will be back next time im in the city!

Went for brunch. Lovely atmosphere in a quaint neighborhood, quiet enough to have a conversation, and food was great if a bit heavier than expected. Pan amb tomaca is amazingly flavorful with or without anchovies.
great place! omg the food is so delicious! we truly enjoyed our dining experience will be back

Service was great. My favorite dishes of the night were the snap pea salad and the sweet corn stew. Both of them were Saturday's special. The snap pea salad were drizzled with smoker dry baby shrimps with a hint of peppercorn oil. The sweet corn stew came out with fresh crab meat, porcini and okra, very interesting and tasty combination. I also love their homemade green tahini, which was mixed in the devil eggs and also brushed at the bottom of the octopus salad. Will try some lamb dishes when I am going back next time:)
Went for brunch. Food was very good while service was just ok.

Upbeat, pleasant environment. Energetic, knowledgeable and hard working servers. Imaginative menu and numerous interesting specials as well. Unusual and interesting wine list. Our family had an outstanding experience from beginning to end. The pulpo, croquettes and fidua with clams, shrimp and house made noodles was memorable. Great place in a beautiful neighborhood.

Absolutely worth a visit.  The daily specials included a wonderful snow pea salad and a delicious dish of scallops.  Both were wonderful, as was the duck and suckling pig.  The service was excellent and happy to make recommendations.
Very good ambiance, delicious tapas. If you want to be outdoors be mindful of mosquitoes.

Everything on their menu is delicious, including the cocktails. Ask to be seated in the backyard. If you’re attempting the Cochinillo, plan the rest of your selections around it; it is fatty and very filling - not as enjoyable when you’ve already made your way through so many small plates and it’s the last thing to arrive.

Everything was excellent - drinks, wine, appetizers, service all impeccable. The only let down was the 2 main courses which were pork and 1/2 chicken, both way overpowered by their respective spices and felt too simple after such amazing appetizers.  It’s a tapas like restaurant so you can easily have a fabulous dinner combined with several types of dishes. The sardines are delicious and the chicken hearts are absolutely delicious. Would definitely recommend!
Every bite was excellent... cozy spot with a wonderful atmosphere as well.

Pretty good but definitely not a 4 or 5 star restaurant based on the food. We ordered: the berenjena (was ok but served with cold bread you would find in someones home), sobrasada (way too much going on..). Our entrees were better: fiduea and gurullos which were both decently good but nothing remotely special. Service was fantastic and atmosphere was fantastic so I am giving 3 stars to their food which I would deem most important in reviewing anyways. Food is not worth the trip or hype.

I went here for brunch and it was phenomenal. Every dish we ordered was so good.

I was disappointed returning after a three-year hiatus, for a birthday dinner with my boyfriend. I remember it being relaxed and lively, with a comfortable, buzzing mixed crowd, encouraged by the communal table. This time I found the space and the service incredibly stiff.  The lights were too bright, the music was more befitting a chain restaurant. The hostess acted like it was a problem that we were 8 minutes late for our reservation, even though the place was empty. Our waitress listed off specials with a pretentious and condescending air, and was way overly formal. I don’t go to white-tablecloth restaurants because I don’t like that, so why are they behaving like that here? On top of that, the food was greasy and less inventive than I remember, it seemed like everything was fried.

What a gem of a place tucked away on the corner of one of Cobble Hill's narrow streets. This place was much more than we expected. The service and presentation was excellent, and the food was delish! Molly, that tends the bar was super friendly and chatted us up, it field like I knew her all my life! I definitely recommend sitting at the bar! Possibly our top 5!
Excellent Spanish restaurant in Brooklyn.

Food is good but Small portions with fat so end up eating a tiny bite. Bad and slow service. Server forgot our order and we waited almost an hour for food. Nobody asked if we wanted another drink or how the food was. Not coming back!

Three of us wandered in here at 12:45 on a Sunday afternoon without a reservation and we were greeted warmly and seated promptly.  Service was great and the food was delicious; we were faced with choosing from many unusual menu items, and everything we got was delicious and well presented. Grilled lamb burger was awesome, as were the two egg dishes (one with artichokes and fava beans, one with crispy lamb hash).  By the time we left, the place was packed, and I could see why... it felt like we stumbled into a real gem in Cobble Hill.  We will definitely be back!
Excellent Spanish restaurant in Brooklyn. Fresh and creative. Great service in a clean and minimal space.

Nothing to say. Amazing experience, service fast and kind. The food is to die for. I am just not sure on the Fritos, they felt a bit heavy.

We came to La Vara for an early Valentine's Day dinner. Everything we ordered was amazing - I even enjoyed the Pipirrana con Grano (cucumber and grain salad) despite not usually liking cucumber. We particularly enjoyed the gurullos (Murcian pasta) and Sobrasada con Miel (spreadable sausage with honey). We shared a pitcher of sangria, which was delicious too, and finished with amazing olive oil ice cream. The staff were friendly and attentive and the atmosphere is lively but not too loud. Overall I highly recommend La Vara!
Very nice tapoas. Interesting combinations.

This is my favorite restaurant in New York! The carabineros are amazing! I always go for the gin and tonic which is very refreshing. The food is consistently scrumptious. Highly recommend!

Absolutely an amazing place to visit . Service is just perfect , Courteous , Respectful ,And knowledgeable . The waitress definitely navigated me through the unknowns of ordering through their . But at the end of the day my hot date was very impressed with me in my selection . So as long as La Vara Can make me look good then they get an automatic 5 star from me . I encourage you to visit this place as it is very impressive .

Genuinely spectacular. One of the best Michelin starred restaurants I've ever been to. It has a casual elegance which immediately puts you at ease but the food is as good as any fine dining place. Strongly recommended for any foodie. The olive oil ice cream is a "shouldn't work but does" example of a chefs experimentation.
Wish there were more stars to give!!!! Delicious !!!

Amazing food but you must have a reservation and be prepared to stay awhile. Best with a group of around four.
Excellent! Food is delicious, service great! It is a must in Brooklyn if you appreciate quality food and ambiance. Don’t miss it!
Fantastic food. We went there for brunch. You should definitely try artichokes in olive oil. They also have very good mild roast from a place around the corner.

Really, really enjoyed the food, service and experience here. I would definitely go back and do recommend it! To be honest I can't understand some of these negative reviews. The space is very comfortable, and there's even a cozy garden in the back to eat outdoors. The server was incredibly knowledgeable about the food preparation and ingredients, as well as very friendly and fun. All the food was absolutely delicious -- lots of preparations were skilled, thoughtful, creative, and unique, food I wouldn't replicate at home because I don't have the skill set (which I always appreciate when eating out). Between three of us we must've ordered around eight dishes (including dessert, no alcohol) which came to under $50pp without tip -- very reasonable in my opinion. The only weak part was dessert, as I think the offerings could be stronger.
The food is really good. Only complaint is that it's a pretty limited menu, but the food and service definitely make it worthwhile.

We spent our anniversary dinner at La Vara. The place is nice and cozy (it might feel crowded to some). The appetizers and main courses were all tapas style and phenomenal! We had deviled eggs, rabbit loin and duck breasts.  The desserts were a bit disappointing, still decent, but not as great as the mains. Overall we were quite impressed, and can definitely recommend La Vara.

There wasn't a wait to get in but there was a wait to get your food! To give credit where credit is due we ordered tapas at the bar but the place only holds about 50 people and it was only half-full when we came before the dinner rush. We ordered about five different small plates expecting to share together  and taste everything  but they bring your Tapas out one at a time... not all at once...who knew! It seemed to take us forever to get to the end of our little appetizer meal which was annoying.
Excellent food, cozy decor, friendly service.
The food is very good here and the specials of the day change constantly. The atmosphere is very nice and the service is always good as well. Highly recommended. Reservations are recomended.
Exquisite food, small portion. Most of the food on menu is bite size.
